- Replaced blocking `delay()` with `millis()`-based scheduling.
- Built four display pages: POWER, ENERGY, COST, DETAIL.
- Added a debounced push button on GPIO4 to cycle pages.

## Decisions made
- **PlatformIO over Arduino IDE.** Config lives in a plain-text file that Git tracks,
  libraries are declared per-project rather than installed globally, and the repo's
  firmware, docs, and dashboard sit in one workspace. Arduino IDE hides its settings
  in a GUI and has no real project structure.
- **Arduino framework over ESP-IDF.** ESP-IDF is the professional native framework
  but much steeper. Arduino has the library ecosystem I need (including the PZEM
  library) and fits the timeline. ESP-IDF noted as a future learning step.
- **`PowerReading` struct as an abstraction boundary.** The display and dashboard
  depend on the function signature, not on where the numbers come from. This means
  the entire pipeline can be built and tested against fake data now, and the PZEM
  swaps in later by changing one function body. It also means that when something
  breaks after integration, I'll know whether it's the PZEM or my code — because my
  code was already proven against known-good data.
- **One big value + two small ones, plus a button** for the OLED layout. Rejected
  showing all five values small (unreadable across a room) and auto-cycling only
  (you wait for the number you want). A wall-socket device is a glance interface, so
  page 1 shows POWER large and works without any interaction. The button is a bonus
  for detail, not a requirement. The dashboard covers the full detail case anyway.
- **GPIO4 for the button.** Avoided GPIO 6–11 (wired to flash), GPIO 34–39
  (input-only, no internal pull-up), and GPIO 0/2/5/12/15 (strapping pins — read at
  reset to decide boot mode, so a button there could stop the board booting).
  GPIO 21/22 are I2C and 16/17 are reserved for the PZEM.

## Problems hit
- **Upload failed with "Please specify upload_port".** PlatformIO found no serial
  ports at all.
- **Red squiggles under the Adafruit `#include` lines** after adding `lib_deps`,
  which looked like the build was broken.
- **`docs/03-design` behaved strangely in Git** — showed as untracked but wouldn't
  list its contents.

## Solutions implemented
- **Driver.** The build itself succeeded (RAM 6.4%, flash 18.3%), so the toolchain
  was fine and the problem was downstream. Device Manager showed "CP2102 USB to UART
  Bridge Controller" under Other devices with a warning triangle. The fact that
  Windows had *named the chip* meant the device had enumerated over USB — which
  requires working data lines. So the cable was fine and the board was alive, and the
  only remaining cause was a missing driver. Windows Update failed to find one
  because Windows 10 stopped distributing CP210x drivers in version 2004. Installed
  the CP210x Universal Windows Driver manually from Silicon Labs; the device moved to
  Ports (COM & LPT) and upload worked.
- **Squiggles.** IntelliSense and the compiler are separate systems. `lib_deps` only
  downloads libraries when you *build*, so IntelliSense was correctly reporting that
  the headers didn't exist yet. Building fixed it — and pulled in Adafruit BusIO
  automatically as a transitive dependency.
- **The folder.** PowerShell's `ls` showed mode `-a----` (archive file) and a length
  of 211 bytes — directories show `d-----` and have no length. It was a *file* named
  `03-design`, created by hitting New File instead of New Folder. Renamed it, created
  the real directory, moved it in as `hardware-pinout.md`.

## Lessons learned
- The build-time RAM figure PlatformIO prints is a **floor, not a total**. Adding the
  OLED only added 840 bytes of static RAM even though the frame buffer alone is 1 KB
   — because the buffer is allocated on the heap at runtime and the compiler can't
  see it. On a chip with no swap, running out of RAM doesn't throw an exception.
- **`delay()` blocks everything.** During `delay(500)` the CPU can't check a button,
  serve a page, or read a sensor. A press that starts and ends inside a delay is
  invisible. Switching to `millis()` gating is what makes concurrent work possible.
- **Mechanical switches bounce** for 5–50 ms. At 240 MHz the ESP32 sees one press as
  five. Software debounce = ignore further transitions until the pin holds steady.
- **`INPUT_PULLUP` inverts the logic** — released reads HIGH, pressed reads LOW.
- **Tactile switches have 4 legs but only 2 contacts.** Legs on the same side are
  permanently joined; you must wire *across* the switch, not along it.
- **My OLED's pin order is `VCC GND SCL SDA`**, swapped versus most tutorials. Read
  the silkscreen, never the tutorial diagram.
- **Comments rot.** After swapping auto-cycle for the button I left a comment saying
  "temporary — the button will replace this trigger" sitting directly above the
  button code. A wrong comment is worse than none.

